Lesson 10: Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) in Python
What is Object-Oriented Programming?

Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a programming style that uses objects and classes to organize code.

OOP helps us create programs that are:

Easy to understand
Easy to manage
Reusable

Many real-world things can be represented as objects.

Examples:

Student

Name
Age
Class

Car

Color
Model
Speed
What is a Class?

A class is a blueprint or template used to create objects.

A class defines the properties and behaviors of an object.

Example:

class Student:
    name = "Hamnah"
    age = 14

Here, Student is a class.

What is an Object?

An object is an instance of a class.

Objects use the information and functions created inside a class.

Example:

class Student:
    name = "Hamnah"
    age = 14

student1 = Student()

print(student1.name)
print(student1.age)

Output:

Hamnah
14
The init() Function

The __init__() function is a special function that runs automatically when an object is created.

It is used to assign values to objects.

Example:

class Student:

    def __init__(self, name, age):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age


student1 = Student("Hamnah", 14)

print(student1.name)
print(student1.age)

Output:

Hamnah
14
Understanding self

The self keyword refers to the current object.

It is used to access variables and functions inside a class.

Example:

class Student:

    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

Here:

self.name belongs to the object.
name is the value passed to the object.
Creating Methods in Classes

A method is a function that is created inside a class.

Example:

class Student:

    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

    def show_name(self):
        print("Student Name:", self.name)


student1 = Student("Hamnah")

student1.show_name()

Output:

Student Name: Hamnah
Inheritance in Python

Inheritance allows one class to use the properties and methods of another class.

It helps reuse code.

Example:

class Person:

    def speak(self):
        print("I can speak")


class Student(Person):

    def study(self):
        print("I can study")


student = Student()

student.speak()
student.study()

Output:

I can speak
I can study
Real-Life Example of OOP

Creating a Student Class:

class Student:

    def __init__(self, name, age, city):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
        self.city = city


student1 = Student("Hamnah", 14, "Karachi")

print(student1.name)
print(student1.age)
print(student1.city)

Output:

Hamnah
14
Karachi
Advantages of OOP

Code Reusability
We can reuse existing code.

Better Organization
Large programs become easier to manage.

Security
Data can be controlled inside objects.

Easy Maintenance
Updating code becomes easier.

Lesson Summary

In this lesson, we learned:

What OOP is
What classes are
What objects are
How to create classes and objects
The use of __init__() function
The purpose of self
Inheritance in Python
